column168: Description Of Events

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO ENSCO, INC. LOCATED AT AMERICAN OIL ROAD IN EL DORADO, AR.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. IN ORDER TO LOAD ADDITIONAL CONTAINERS ONTO THE TRAILER.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP CLOSURE OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED THE FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDY DRI.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION IDENTIFIED THAT THE GASKET BETWEEN THE TOP CLOSURE AND THE CONTAINER BODY WAS MISSING ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. ****** IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, LOADING PERSONNEL WILL BE RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL DRUMS ARE CLOSED UTILIZING ALL REQUIRED DRUM COMPONENTS.  FURTHERMORE, ANY CONTAINER FOUND NOT TO BE IN SHIPPABLE CONDITION MUST NOT BE SHIPPED UNTIL THE DEFICIENCY IS CORRECTED.
DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK WHEN VENT ALARM FAILED CAUSING SPILL TO ESCAPE ON TO THE GROUND.  OIL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY .
THE MATERIAL WAS IN A 16 GALON PLASTIC DRUM.  THE LOAD SHIFTED RESULTING IN THE LID POPPING OFF OF THE DRUM AND CREATING THE SPILL.  ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND DRUMMED FOR SHIPMENT.

WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED A STRONG ODOR WAS DETECTED.  THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO AN OUTDOOR DOCK AWAY FROM POPULATION.  WHEN THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 4 BAGS WERE LEAKING PRODUCT.  2 BAGS WERE DAMAGED & HAD TAPE OVER THE HOLES (LEAKING).  1 BAG WAS LEAKING AT THE CORNER.  1 BAG WAS LEAKING DUE TO A FORKLIFT HOLE & THE SKID WAS TURNED AROUND TOWARD THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  ACCORDING TO THE MSDS SHEET THIS PRODUCT IS EXTREMELY DANGEROUS.  THIS PRODUCT IS MUCH TO HAZARDOUS TO SHIP IN PAPER BAGS.  SOME THINGS NEED TO BE DONE IMMEDIATELY ABOUT THE SHIPPING CONTAINERS THAT THIS PRODUCT IS SHIPPED IN.

PLASTIC LID ON JUG WAS OVERTIGHTENED WHICH CAUSED IT TO CRACK & COME OFF. WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED, THIS SHIPMENT WAS ON REAR OF TRAILER & WE FOUND 1-1 GALLON PLASTIC JUG HAD COMPLETELY EMPTIED ONTO THE FLOOR OF UNIT.  WE CLEANED IT UP WITH CLAY BASED FLOOR DRY & CARDBOARD.  THE EMPTY JUG WAS DISPOSED OF ALONG WITH THE BROKEN LID.

ON 5-5-95 AT APPROXIMATELY 0015 HOURS, CHICAGO CENTRAL & PACIFIC RAILROAD SWITCH CREW SMELL THE ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM TANK CAR ACFX 17297, WHILE IT WAS IN THE TRAIN YARD LOCATED IN FORT DODGE, IOWA. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND COULD BE HEARD COMING FROM THE DOME OF THE TANK CAR. CC DISPATCHERS THEN CONTACTED FARMLAND INDUSTRIES, THE SHIPPER IN FORT DODGE AND ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. FARMLAND THEN DISPATCHED A REPAIR PERSON. UPON THAT PERSONS ARRIVAL THE GAUGING DEVICE SEAL WAS TIGHTENED THUS STOPPING THE MINOR LEAK. TANK CAR WAS SECURED AT 0100 HOURS, SAME DATE. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 25 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE.

column168: THE ABOVE SHIPMENT WAS LOADED OUT ONTO OUR TRAILER WITH ONE CONTAINER LOADED ON ITS SIDE. MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO APPLICABLE REGULATIONS. THE CONTAINER WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. THE LOADING TERMINAL HAS BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM AND INSTRUCTED ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES. ORIGIN TERMINAL WAS INSTRUCTED TO TALK TO THE SHIPPER TO ENSURE THE LIDS WERE SECURE IN THE FUTURE.

PAINT SPLASHED IN DOCKMANS FACE AND ON TRAILER WALLS DOCKMANS EYES WERE WASHED WITH SALINE SOLUTION AND TAKEN TO EMERGENCY ROOM TO HAVE SAME DONE AGAIN AND WAS RELEASED SAME DAY. APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS WAS SPLASHED OUT DURING LOADING.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 HOURS ON MAY 3, 1995, THE BURLINGTON NORTHERN OFFICE AT BELLINGHAM, WASHINGTON WAS NOTIFIED BY THE SKAGIT COUNTY OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING TANK CAR ON THE BN SIDING TRACK AT SOUTH MT. VERNON, WASHINGTON. RAILROAD RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM EVERETT AND SEATTLE, WASHINGTON TRAVELED TO THE AREA OF ANDERSON ROAD AND HIGHWAY 99 IN MT. VERNON, WASHINGTON WHERE AN INCIDENT COMMAND CENTER HAD BEEN ESTABLISHED BY SKAGIT COUNTY FIRE DISTRICT NO. 3. THE INCIDENT COMMANDER INDICATED THAT A SMALL AREA APPROXIMATELY ONE BLOCK AROUND THE INCIDENT SITE HAD BEEN EVACUATED ON A VOLUNTARY BASIS AND INVOLVED FOUR BUSINESSES AND ONE HOME. HE ALSO INDICATED THAT TWO CITIZENS HAD BEEN TREATED AND RELEASED AT A LOCAL HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM FOR THROAT IRRITATION AND NAUSEA. TANK CAR GATX 14193, FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (CRUDE SULPHATE TURPENTINE), 3, UN1993, WAS INSPECTED BY THE RAILROAD RESPONDERS AND FOUND TO HAVE A SMALL LEAK AROUND THE STEM OF THE TOP-OPERATED, BOTTOM-OUTLET VALVE, INDICATING POSSIBLE DEFECTIVE PACKING GLAND. THE CAR WAS MOVED ONE MILE SOUTH OF MT. VERNON TO A RURAL GRADE CROSSING WHERE EMPLOYEES OF UNION TANK CAR COMPANY, AT THE REQUEST OF THE CONSIGNEE, MADE REPAIRS TO THE PACKING GLAND, EFFECTIVELY STOPPING LEAK. REPAIRS WERE COMPLETE AT 1500 HRS. THE CAR WAS PLACED ON SOUTH END OF THE SIDING TRACK FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE ON MAY 4, 1995.

SKID BROKE DURING TRANSIT AND ALLOWED DRUM TO OVER TURN IN TRAILER. TRAILER WAS PARKED AND AREA SECURED. VENDOR WAS CALLED AND SHIPPER/CHEMTREC NOTIFIED. ON 5/4/95 APPROX. 0200 HRS VEH #1 WAS PROCEEDING NORTH ON I-81 AT EXIT #8 NEAR CHAMBERSBURG, PA. WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED CARGO TANK #1077 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT THRU THE OUTER WRAPPER O THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER STOPPED.  SECURRED THE UNIT AND NOTIFIED THE COMPANY TERMINAL AT KENVIL N.J. (ALL OF THE PROPER AUTHORITIES) WERE NOTIFIED.  ANOTHER TRACTOR & CARGO TANK WAS DISPATCHED FROM KENVIL, N.J. TO THE SCENE & A SECOND WAS TRANSFERRED FROM CARGO TANK 1077 TO CARGO TANK 1603.  FROM THE TIME THE TRANSFER STARTED UNTIL THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WAS A TOTAL OF 45 MINUTES.  SUPERIORS COMPANY UNIT 1077 HAD EXTERNAL, INTERNAL, PRESSURE, LEAKAGE, THICKNESS TEST COMPLETED ON 12/23/94 & THE FEDERAL ANNUAL SAFETY INSPECTION OF 4/4/95.  THE PENN. STATE POLICE MOTOR CARRIER DIVISION COMPLETED AN INSPECTION FO THE UNIT AT THE SCENE & NO VIOLATIONS WERE FOUND.

PRODUCT IN BOTTOM PALLET WAS LIQUID AND APPROX 5 GALLONS ESCAPED ORIGINAL CONTAINER. APPROX 11 POUNDS OF GRANULAR NEMAUR 15% SPILLED INTO ESCAPED LIQUID. DURING THE MORNING PACKAGE SORT OF MAY 2, AT APPROX. 0530 CST, TWO CARGO HANDLERS WERE OVERCOME BY FUME INHALATION FROM SUBJECT PACKAGE.  EMPLOYEES WERE TAKEN TO A FRESH AIR AREA AND EMT'S WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS ISOLATED AND THE SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST SUITED UP AND INSPECTED THE PACKAGE.  THE INNER PACKAGE SHOWED A SMALL LEAK AND THE FUMES WERE VERY STRONG.  THE CONSIGNEE PROVIDED A MSDS WHICH REVEALED THAT THE LYONDELL RESIN #90 WAS BASICALLY A NAPHTHA MATERIAL AND HAD A FLASH POINT WHICH FELL INTO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID (CLASS 3) CATEGORY.  THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT SHIPPED AS A DANGEROUS GOOD.  EMPLOYEE WERE TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM FOR FURTHER TESTING AND OBSERVATION.  THEY WERE RELEASED LATER THAT MORNING.  HOUSTON AREA FAA SECURITY OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND AGENT CAME OVER THAT DAY TO CONDUCT AN INVESTIGATION ON THIS SHIPMENT.  THEY LATER GAVE PERMISSION FOR THIS SHIPMENT TO BE RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PICKED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE BEFORE THE DG SPECIALIST COULD DOCUMENT ALL OF THE PACKAGING INFORMATION NECESSARY TO COMPLETE THE BACK OF THIS REPORT RELATED TO PACKAGING.

column168: PACKAGE CAME IN AN INBOUND FLIGHT INTO MEMPHIS HUB OPERATIONS. CREWMEMBERS COMPLAINED OF STRONG GASOLINE ODORS AND REQUESTED MEMPHIS HUB DANGEROUS GOODS SPILL PERSONNEL MEET THE AIRCRAFT UPON ARRIVAL.  THE HAZMAT LOAD ABOARD THE AIRCRAFT WAS UNLOADED UNTIL A THREE PIECE SHIPMENT CONTAINING RACK SAMPLES OF GASOLINE WAS FOUND ISOLATED AND OPENED.  UPON OPENING IT WAS REVEALED THAT THE GLASS BOTTLES IN THE THREE PIECES APPARENTLY HAD NOT BEEN SEALED PROPERLY.  THIS RESULTED IN SLIGHT SPILLAGE AND RESIDUE ON THE TOP OF AT LEAST ONE OF THE BOTTLES IN ALL THREE BOXES IN THE SHIPMENT. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURES.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: ON MAY 1, 1995, A PRODUCT SPILL OCCURED AT FUTURE FOAM IN COUNCIL BLUFF, IOWA.  THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT HE HAD TO USE TWO SECTIONS OF HOSE TO REACH THE CUSTOMERS LINE.  THE HOSES WERE LAID OUT AND THE PLANT OPERATOR CONNECTED THE HOSES TOGETHER AND ALSO CONNECTED THE HOSES TO HIS LINE. APPROXIMATELY THIRTY MINUTE INTO THE UNLOADING, OUR DRIVER, KENNY SHEPARD, NOTICED THE ASPHALT WAS WET AT THE HOSE HE SAW THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE CAM LOCK FITTING WHERE THE HOSES WERE CONNECTED.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE CONNECTION TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLAGE.  THE PLANT PERSONNEL DECIDED TO REPOSITION OUT UNIT AND USE THEIR HOSE TO COMPLETE THE UNLOADING.  WHEN THE UNIT RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL THE PRODUCT HOSE WAS INSPECTED AND TESTED FOR LEAKS.  THE HOSE WAS PRESSURED TO 100 PSI WHILE UNDER WATER AND NO LEAK WAS FOUND.  WE CHECKED THE EARS ON THE FEMALE END OF THE HOSE AND FOUND THAT THEY WERE NOT WORN.  WE THEN FOCUSED ON THE TYPE MATERIAL WE ARE USING FOR OUR GASKETS.  THE GASKET IN A N ENVELOPE DESIGN WITH A RUBBER CORE WRAPPED WITH TEFLON.  IN DISCUSSION WITH OUR QUALITY COMMITEE MEMBERS AND OTHER DRIVERS, IT HAS BEEN IDENTIFIED THAT THIS STYLE GASKET IS SOMETIMES VERY DIFFICULT TO SEAL OFF. IT USUALLY REQUIRED THE USE OF A THIN METAL SHIM PLACED UNDER THE EARS OF THE FITTING CAUSING THE GAKSET TO BE SQUEEZED TIGHTER.

NOTIFIED TANYA RICHARDSON IN OFFICE THAT TANK WAS LEAKING. THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED.  TESTED THE PRODUCT LEAKING.  THE PRODUCT WAS THE HAZARDOUS COMMODITY.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, ENTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, WAS CALLED TO RESPOND.  PORT OF HOUSTON SECURED THE AREA.  ABSORBANT WAS PUT ON THE ASPHALT/CONCRETE SURFACE.  TANK SUTU104098 WAS IMPORTED TO SEA-LAND HOUSTON OF THE DELAWARE BAY.  THE DANGEROUS CARGO MANIFEST INDICATED UN1993, FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (TRIMETHYL AND DIMETHYL ETHYL PYRIDINE).  THE OCEAN FREIGHT BILL INDICATED UN2325 (TRIMETHYL BENZENE).  I CONTACTED CHEMTREC JOE BABER TO CONTACT SHIPPER SUTTON TO CLARIFY COMMODITY ON TANK.  NOTIFIED NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER OF SPILLED PRODUCT ON GROUND.  REPORT NUMBER 289552.  NOTIFIED TNRCC LAND COMMISSIONER OPERATOR 64.  RECEIVED CALL BACK FROM JOHN WILSON TO ADVISE PRODUCT IS ENICHEM THE CONSIGNEE PRODUCT "MESITYLENE".  HE ADVISED ME TO CALL CHEMTREC FOR HAZARDOUS INFORMATION.  CONTACTED CHEMTREC JOE BABER FOR INFORMATION.  HE CONFIRMED COMMODITY MESITYLENE IS TRIMETHYL BENZENE UN2325.  HE FAXED A COPY OF MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET TO THE TERMINAL FOR OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  IT WAS FIRST THOUGHT THERE WAS PROBLEM WITH THE VALVE.  EMTECH RESPONSE TEAM PUMPED APPROXIMATELY 220 GALLON OF PRODUCT INTO 4 DRUMS.  THE PRODUCT WAS PUT INTO NEW DRUMS.  THE PRODUCT WAS NOT CONTAMINATED.  THE CONSIGNEE ENICHEM WILL BE ABLE TO TAKE DELIVERY OF THE TANK AND FOUR DRUMS.  THE PRODUCT EXPANDED DUE TO THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE.  THE TANK WAS LOADED BEYOND CAPACITY.  WHEN PRODUCT EXPANDED, IT FLOODED OVER INTO THE DOME COVER.  LESS THAN TWO GALLONS SPILLED ONTO CONCRETE AND ASPHALT.  COMPLETED AT 9:36PM.  I CALLED JOHN WILSON TO ADVISE OF FINDINGS.

column168: A VAN LOAD OF DRUMS (80 DRUMS) WERE PICKED UP AT TRW SAFETY SYSTEMS, QUEEN CREEK, AZ. ON MAY 2, 1995.  THE LOAD WAS SCHEDULED FOR DELIVERY AT TRADE WASTE INCINERATION IN SAUGET, IL.  THE DRIVER DROVE FROM QUEEN CREEK, AZ. TO GRANTS, NM. WHERE HE TOOK HIS LAY-OVER.  ON MAY 3, 1995, AS THE DRIVER WAS DOING HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION, HE DISCOVERED THAT SOME MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT FROM THE VAN (SEE MANIFEST).  THE DRIVER IMMDEIATELY CONFINED THE MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE ASPHALT.  FLOOR DRY ABSORBENT WAS SPREAD ON AND AROUND THE PERIMETER OF THE SPILL TO CONTAIN THE MATERIAL FROM FURTHER MIGRATION.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED THE MP ENVIRONMENTAL (MP) PHOENIX OFFICE TO NOTIFY DISPATCH OF THE INCIDENT.  TRW PERSONNEL WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION.  AFTER NOTIFYING TRW, MP SENT A TRUCK AND VAN TRAILER TO THE SCENE IN GRANTS, NM, THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED FROM ONE VAN TO ANOTHER.  WHEN TRANSFERRING THE DRUMS IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT TWO DRUMS HAD SIGNS OF SEEPAGE ALONG THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUMS.  THE TWO DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED INTO METAL 85 GALLON OVERPACK CONTAINERS AND THE TRAILER AND ASPHALT WERE DECONTAMINATED.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO TAKE THE LOAD ONTO TRADE WASTE INCIDENRATION IN SAUGET, IL. ON MAY 5, 1995 TRW AND MP ENVIRONMENTAL HAVE DECIDED THAT IN THE FUTURE, DRUMS LOADED ON VAN TRAILERS WILL NOT BE PRE-LOADED.  THE DRIVER WILL INSPECT THE DRUMS AS THEY AREA LOADED FOR ANY SIGNS OF DEFECTS THAT COULD CAUSE LEAKAGE.

THE SALVAGE DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIM CREDIT. THE MINOR SPILLAGE HAD EVAPORATED.

THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM FOUND THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE CAME LOOSE AND THERE WAS NO WAY OF TIGHTING IT. THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED AND SUGGESTED TO LET THE CYLINDER RELEASE ALL PRODUCT. column168: WHEN CONTAINER CASU 69802, LOADED WITH 68 DRUMS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLID, 8, UN1823, PG 11, WAS UNLOADED FROM FLATCAR TTWX 978577, LIQUID WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM IT. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO DETERMINED THE POSSIBLE HAZARD OF THE LEAKING LIQUID AND PERFORM REMEDIAL ACTIONS, IF NECESSARY. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKING LIQUID HAD A PH OF 14. WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED, IT WAS FOUND THAT THREE DRUMS IN THE BOTTOM TIER HAD BEEN DAMAGED BY DRUMS IN TOP TIER, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF SOLID SODIUM HYDROXIDE. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WERE SEVERAL HOLES IN THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER THAT HAD ALLOWED RAIN WATER TO ENTER THE CONTAINER AND MIX WITH THE SPILLED LADING, CAUSING THE CORROSIVE LIQUID RELEASE. AFTER THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACKS AND THE SPILLAGE NEUTRALIZED, THE SHIPMENT WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.
IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT. 3 1 GALLON CONTAINERS WERE DISCOVERED TO BE CRUSHED AND LEAKING AT THE FUTURE POINT.
CARTON DISCOVERED WHEN UNLOADING TRAILER, WAS ALREADY DAMAGED. RECOOPED INTO RECOVERY DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON SUNDAY 05-14-95 AT 2000 HOURS, THE FREIGHT OPERATIONS MANAGER ON DUTY WAS INFORMED THAT TRAILER 17-2891, AN OVERHEAD FOR MANCHESTER. NH, WAS LEAKING. THE F.O.M. HAD THE TRAILER PUT AGAINST THE DOCK AND AFTER CHECKING THE BILLS TO IDENTIFY WHAT COULD BE LEAKING, HE OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR. THE F.O.M. FOUND ONE DRUM THAT APPEARED TO HAVE SOME LIQUID ON TOP. THE DRUM PINCHED BETWEEN OTHER 55 GALLON DRUMS ON THE TRAILER AND IT APPEARED THAT THE DRUM HAD OPENED UP AT THE BUNG ON TOP. A SMALL AMOUNT OF CORROSIVE LIQUID ON THE DRUM AND FLOOR OF THE TRAILER (1/2 GALLON). THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERED AND THE LIQUID CLEANED UP AND HELD FOR DISPOSAL. THE DRUM WILL BE HELD AT SMA UNTIL WE ARE SURE THAT IT HAS NO OTHER LEAKS BEFORE MOVING TO DESTINATION. TRAILER INVOLVED WILL BE MOVED TO A SHOP LOCATION FOR PROPER CLEANING. ORIGIN TERMINAL WILL BE ADVISED OF POOR LOADING PRACTICES.

FUTURE MOVEMENTS OF SKIDS CONTAINING LARGE NUMBERS OF BOXES WILL BE SHRINK WRAPPED.

PACKAGE DID NO FAIL.  SPILL OCCURED WHEN A HOSE DISCONNECTED FROM THE METER USED TO DETERMINE THE AMOUNT DELIVERED.  VEHICLE USED TO TRANSPORT THE PRODUCT WAS A STRIGHT TRUCK EQUIPPED WITH A POWER-TAKE OFF (PTO) USED TO POWER A PUMP.  PRODUCT WAS PUMPED FROM A 55 GALLON DRUM VIA A HOSE WHICH RAN THE PRODUCT THROUGH A METER TO COUNT THE GALLONS DELIVERED.  THE HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO THE METER WITH CLAMPS.  THE CLAMPS HAD WORKED THEMSELVES LOOSE, AND WHEN THE PTO WAS ENGAGED, THE PRESSSURE CAUSED THE HOSE TO SEPERATE FROM THE METER SPILLING THE PRODUCT ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE TUCSON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY RESPONDED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TOOK CHARGE OF THE INCIDENT AND HANDLED THE CLEAN-UP. ROLLINS DEDICATED CARRIAGE SERVICES, INC.  CONTRACTED WITH SENETEC, A LOCAL ARIZONA COMPANY, TO HANDLE SURFACE AND GROUND CLEAN -UP AND REPLACEMENT.  HAZARDOUS WASTE REMOVAL WAS HANDLED BY ROLLINS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  THE PUMP AND RELATED APPARTUS WAS TAKEN TO A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PUMP REPAIRMAN.  THE CONNECTION WAS REPAIRED, BUT NO ADDITIONAL DELIVERIES WILL BE MADE UNTIL A MORE SECURE CONNECTION HAS BEEN DEVISED FOR THE HOSE-METER CONNECTION.

column168: WHEN THE SCHNEIDER NATIONAL DRIVER PULLED UP TO THE DOCK AND OPENED THE DOORS. THE DOCK WORKERS NOTICED AN ODOR AND REPORTED THIS TO THEIR ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER. THE ADVANCED TRANSPORT DOCK WORKER CALLED SCHNEIDER NATIONAL EXTENDED COVERAGE AND TOLD THEM TO CALL THE EPA. THE EPA CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND A HAZ MAT CLEAN-UP FIRM WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. THE INITIAL ASSUMPTION WAS THAT THE POISON GAS WAS LEAKING. AFTER THE CLEAN-UP FIRM ARRIVED, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL OF THE POISON GAS CYLINDERS WERE FULL AND THE NEXT LIKELY CHOICE WAS THE PESTICIDE (44% CARBOFURAN ). EACH OF THE 13 PACKAGES HAVE VENTS AND IT WAS THOUGHT THAT THESE VENTS EMITTED THE ODOR. THE OWNER OF THE PESTICIDE CONTAINERS STAND FIRM THAT THEY CAN NOT DO THAT WHEN EMPTY. SO IN CONCLUSION, ALL WE HAVE TO REPORT IS AN ODOR. THE EPA WAS CALLED OUT, HAZ MAT TEAM, CLEAN-UP FIRM, BUT NO EVIDENCE OF A HAZ MAT RELEASE. OUR STATE OF WI DOT SAFETY SPECIALIST ROY STACEY INDICATED THAT WE SHOULD STILL SEND IN A 5800.1 FORM BUT EXPLAIN THAT NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.

column168: SOO LINE RAILROAD TRAIN #379-24, COLLIED WITH SOO LINE RAILROAD TRAIN #580-25, THAT RESULTED IN 10 CARS AND 2 LOCOMOTIVES BEING DERAILED OFF OF TRAIN #379-24, AND 3 CARS AND 2 LOCOMOTIVES BEING DERAILED OFF OF TRAIN 580-25.  GATX 48021, WAS ONE OF THE 10 CARS DERAILED OFF OF TRAIN 379-24, AND SUFFERED DAMAGE TO ITS DRAFT SILL THAT HAD BUCKLED UNDER THE CAR CAUSING A SLIGHT TEAR AT THE POINT WHERE THE DRAFT SILL ATTACHES TO THE TANK SHELL, AND IT MAY HAVE RELEASED A SMALL AMOUNT OF AMMONIA.  THE FOXHOLM, ND.  FIRE DEPARTMENT, SMELLED THE AMMONIA, AND BEGAN TO EVACUATE LOCAL RESIDENTS (APPROXIMATELY 20) FROM THEIR HOMES, AND APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES LATER, BEGAN ALLOWING THEM TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES.  GATX 48021, WAS CLEANED AND PURGED OF ANY HAZRADOUS RESIDUE AT FOXHOLM, ND. AND WILL BE RETURNED TO ITS HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  THE WASTE AMMONIA WAS GIVE TO A LOCAL FARMER TO USE AS A FERTILIZER SOLUTION, THERE WAS NO ADDITIONAL CLEAN UP NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING A 55 GAL PLASTIC DRUM OF COMPOUND CLEANING LIQUID (PHOSPHORIC ACID), 8, NA1760, PGII, FROM OUR VEHICLE ONTO THE DOCK OF THE CONSIGNEE, A SPILL OCCURRED.  THE VEHICLE STANDS APPROX. TWO TO THREE INCHES HIGHER THAN THE DOCK SURFACE.  THE DRIVER, UTILIZING A BARREL JACK, PULLED THE JACK CONTAINING THE DRUM FROM THE VEHICLE TO THE DOCK.  THE DRUM BOUNCED AND WAS PUNCTURED ON THE FEET OF THE BARREL JACK.  DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO TURN THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE DUE TO ITS WEIGHT.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT ONTO THE DOCK AND INTO THE SEWER.  THE PHILA. FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED AND THE PHILA. WATER DEPT.  THE SITUATION WAS REMEDIATED BY BOTH PARTIES AND THE CONSIGNEE'S CLEANUP COMPANY, ETC.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURENCES OF THIS KIND, CBL IS DEVELOPING A TRAINING PROGRAM TO ADDRESS LOADING/UNLOADING FREIGHT ON UNEVEN SURFACES. ALSO, WE WILL EXPAND OUR EMERGENCY PROCEDURE POLICY TO INCLUDE ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATION REQUIREMENTS.

CENTRAL TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS ENROUTE FROM TRUCK STOP TO TERMINAL IN PAULSBORO (APPROX. 2 MILES).  UNKNOWN CAME UP BEHIND UNIT RIGHT BEFORE HE TURNED INTO TERMINAL AND POINTED AT THE TANK.  DRIVER THEN NOTICED HE HAD PRODUCT ON SIDE OF TANK.  HE PULLED INTO TANK WASH AND CHECKED TANK. PRESSURE REFILL VALVE ON BACK DOME LID HAD COME LOOSE.  DRIVER WASHED DOME OFF AT TANK WASH AND GOT DOME TIGHTENED BACK DOWN.

column168: THE BOX WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR.  THE BOX WAS OPENED AND A SMALL AMOUNT HAD LEAKED FROM THE FRICTION LID.  THE CANS DID HAVE CLIPS, BUT THE CANS WERE ABLE TO MOVE FREELY IN THE BOX.  WE BELIEVE THIS CAUSED THE LEAK. ICAO CHAPTER 1-1.1.9 REQUIRES THAT INNER PACKAGINGS MUST BE PACKED, SECURED, OR CUSHIONED TO PREVENT MOVEMENT OR LEAKAGE.  IN THIS CASE, WE HAD BOTH MOVEMENT & LEAKAGE.  THE SHIPPER & FAA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION.

THE FAA & SHIPPER HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.  THE FAA HAS INSPECTED THE FREIGHT & RELEASED IT.

column168: THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT APPROX 1200 HRS 22 MAY 95 - ONE OF OUR TRUCKS LEFT OUR NEW TRIPOLI MAGAZINE SITE LOADED WITH 200 CO(11,00#) OF 40% EXTRA GEL DYNAMITE.A SHORT TIME LATER A LOCAL PASSERBY INFORMED US THAT OUR TRUCK WAS OVERTURNED ON MOSSERVILLE RD APPROX 2 MILES FROM OUR SITE. THERE WERE NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED, OUR DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED AND THE ONLY PROPERTY DAMAGED WAS TO OUR VEHICLE.  THERE WAS NO LOSS OF PRODUCT OR DAMAGE TO PACKAGING.  THE LOCAL FIRE CO. WAS NOTIFIED WHO INTURN REPORTED THE ACCIDENT TO THE PA STATE POLICE WHO INVESTIGATED THE ACCIDENT AND THE LOCAL EMERGENCY PLANNING COMMITTEE, WHO DID NOT RESPOND. OUR PERSONNEL ATTENDED THE SCENE AND DIRECTED TRAFFIC AROUND THE ACCIDENT UNTIL THE FIRE COMPANY ARRIVED AND CLOSED THE ROAD.  THEY CRIBBED THE OVERTURNED TRUCK SO OUR PERSONNEL COULD THEN TRANSFER THE LOAD FROM THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE TO ANOTHER TRUCK AND WE COMPLETED OUR DELIVERY.  THE FIRE CO. DECIDED TO EVACUATE ONE PERSON FROM A FARM HOUSE LOCATED A FEW HUNDRED YARDS DOWN THE ROAD WHILE WE TRANSFERED THE LOAD.  THE ROAD WAS CLOSED TO TRAFFIC APPROX. 2.5 HRS. FROM THE TIME THE FIRE CO CLOSED THE ROAD UNTIL THE WRECKER TOWED OUR VEHICLE BACK TO OUR SITE.  ALTHOUGH A TIRE CHECK WAS PREFORMED BEFORE THE SUBJECT VEHICLE LEFT THE MAGAZINE IT APPEARS A FLAT ON THE OUTSIDE RIGHT REAR TIRE CAUSED THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL WHEN IT ENTERED A CURVE TO THE LEFT AND SUBSEQUENTLY OVERTURNED ONTO A BANK ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROAD. A MEMO WAS ISSUED TO ALL EMPLOYEES EMPHASIZING THE IMPORTANCE OF ROUTES, SPEED LIMITS, TIRE CHECKS AND LOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AND WAS BACKED IN ON A 45 ANGLE (THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WAS LOWER THAN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER) WHEN THE DRIVER DETECTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL SEEPING FROM THE CLEAN OUT CAP NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER BACKED THE TRAILER UP FURTHER, OFF THE GRADE, LEVELING THE TRAILER OFF AND RELIEVING THE PRESSURE OF MATERIAL ON THE CLEAN OUT CAP WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK AND PERMITTED THE COMPLETION OF THE DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. AN EXAMINATION OF THE CLEAN OUT CAP AFTERWARDS REVEALED A CRACKED GASKET TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.

A FLAT BED TRAILER TRANSPORTING A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM HOLTRACHEM MANUFACTURING COMPANY LOCATED AT ROUTE 15 RIVER ROAD IN ORRINGTON, ME TO STABLEX CANADA LOCATED AT 760 INDUSTRIAL BLVD. IN BLAINVILLE QUEBEC. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP IN ORDER TO OBTAIN REST. PRIOR TO RESUMING THE TRIP, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A ROUTINE LOAD CHECK AND DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED FROM A SMALL CRACK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE ROLL-OFF CAN ONTO THE DECK OF THE TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND SPREAD SPEEDI DRY ON THE FREE LIQUID. THIS MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN THE ROLL-OFF LIQUID. THIS MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER. THE VEHICLE WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPERS LOCATION WHERE IT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO AN ALTERNATE CONTAINER FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE PROPERLY CLOSED OR NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

column168: GATX 58422 NOTD LEAKING PRODUCT AROUND MANWAY COVER DURING SWITCHING OPERATION.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  IVESTIGATION BY SHIPPER REVEALED THIS CAR WAS MOVING AS AN EMPTY (RESIDUE) SHIPMENT AND HAD BEEN INADVERTENTLY RELEASED AND PULLED FROM THE CONSIGNEE BEFORE UNLOADING. WHEN THE CAR ARRIVED BACK AT THE SHIPPERS PLANT THE MAWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSENED IN ANTICIPATION OF RELOADING THE CAR AND THEN WHEN THE CAR WAS SWITCHED FOR PLACEMENT THE CONTENTS SLOSHED OUT AROUND THE LOOSE MANWAY COVER.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED BY A SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE AND THE CAR WAS SAFE FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: GATX 13891 NOTED LEAKING BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL DURING UNLOADING OPERATION.  UNLOADING PERSONNEL HAD PUT PRESSURE ON THE CAR TO FACILITATE UNLOADING CAUSING A LINING FAILURE AND THE SUBSEQUENT LOSS OF BETWEEN 200 AND 800 GALLONS OF PRODUCT THROUGH THE WEEP HOLE ON THE UNLOADING VALVE. UNLODING OPERATION WAS COMPLETED USING ALTERNATE MEANS, THE CAR WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER REMAINING CONTENTS NEUTRALIZED AND THE CAR HOMESHOPPED FOR FURTHER REPAIRS.  ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE WAS CONFINED TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA, MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND ALL CONTAMINATION REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

CONTAINER WAS OPENED AS A RANDOM AUDIT BY FRA AND DPUC HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTORS.  INSPECTION REVEALED THREE CARGO TANKS TO BE LEAKING:  A) TWO 2-INCH PLUGS LOOSE (1/3 AND 1/4 TURN REQUIRED TO TIGHTEN)  B) TOP VENT PLUG FAILED (LID INSTALLED IN ITS PLACE)  C) 2-INCH BUNG LOOSE (TIGHTENED 1 1/2 TURNS)  PRODUCT RELEASED HAD HARDENED AND HAD NOT ESCAPED FROM CONTAINER.  CONSIGNEE RESPONDED TO MAKE PERMANENT REPLACEMENTS AND TO ENSURE LOAD WAS SAFE TO RELEASE FOR DELIVERY.

column168: AT 0855 HOURS ON MAY 15TH, PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISION OF OHIO INSPECTOR DISCOVERED PLMX 33046 "VENTING" IN SHARONVILLE YARD.  A RESPONSE UNIT FROM SUN OIL WHICH WAS CALLED, ARRIVED AND CHANGED THE "O" RING IN THE SAFETY VALVE, DEPARTING AT 7 PM.

AT 1130 HOURS ON MAY 22ND IN FRONTIER YRD, A YARDMASTER NOTICED PRODCUT ON THE SHELL OF UTLX 14115.  A NORANDA RESPONSE TEAM FOUND AND REPLACED THE RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISC.  THEY CLEANED THE CAR AND NEUTRALIZED THE PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  THE CAR THEN RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.
DRIVER STOPPED AT THE PORT OF ENTRY AT SPOKANE, WA.  THERE WAS A LEAK FROM THE FIRST COMPARTMENT.

DRIVER WAS OFF-LOADING CARGO TANK.  HOOKED TO A PIPE ON OUTSIDE OF BUILDING.  STORAGE TANK WAS INSIDE BUILDING.  CONSIGNEE CAME OUT AND TOLD THE DRIVER TO SHUT OFF PRODUCT AND HIS STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING. DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND WENT INSIDE AND PRODUCT WAS RUNNING OUT OF TANK WHICH WAS ON A CONCRETE FLOOR AND INSIDE A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT WALL.  CONSIGNEE PUMPED OUT PIT AND THEN THE DRIVER FINISHED OFF-LOADING CARGO TANK. DRIVER STATED APPROXIMATELY 400 GALS RAN OUT OF STORAGE TANK INTO CONTAINMENT PIT.  NO INJURIES DUE TO OVERFLOW.

RAILCAR WAS INSPECTED 0130 HRS 5/15/95 BY UNION PACIFIC SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS KEN DECHANT, AT WHICH TIME MATERIAL WAS NOTED DRIPPING AT A SLOW RATE FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  FURTHER INSPECTION DISCLOSED THREE OF THE FOUR BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE BASE FLANGE BOLTS WERE LOOSE, ALTHOUGH THE PRIMARY SOURCE OF LEAKAGE APPEARED TO BE THE OPERATING HANDLE PACKING RETAINER.  TIGHTENING OF THE PACKING RETAINER SCRES, AND THE FLANGE BOLTS, WHICH STOPPED ALL LEAKAGE.  ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED, WITH NO POOLING OR GROUND SATURATION NOTED.  NO INJURIES ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT. CHEMTREC REPORT NUMBER 35637.

A RAILROAD TANK CAR WAS INVOLVED IN A TRAIN DERAILMENT ON 5/26/95 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:05 PM. AS A RESULT THE CAR SPILLED ABOUT 27,000 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL. THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED: LOCAL FIRE DEPT., HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONSE TEAMS, NTSB, NRC, EPA, CHEMTREC, NYS DEC, NYS DOT AND THE FRA. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (ECOLOGY & ENVIRONMENT, LANCASTER, NY) WAS ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM AND IMMEDIATELY PROCEEDED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL. A VACCUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO REMOVE THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE SCENE. MORE THAN 24,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAS BEEN RECOVERED THUS FAR. OVER A PERIOD OF ABOUT 10 DAYS, SOME OF THE MATERIAL ENTERED A NEARBY CREEK THROUGH HILLSIDE SHALE, CONTAINMENT BOOMS AND ABSORBENT PADS WERE PLACED FOR COLLECTION PURPOSES. SEVERAL HUNDRED TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WILL BE REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. A PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION (ABOUT 24 HOURS) TOOK PLACE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT IS UNDER INVESTIGATION.

DOCK WORKER WAS TRYING TO MOVE BACK FURNITURE WHICH WAS PLACED ON TOP OF SKIDS.  NO DUNNAGE WAS USED TO PROTECT THE BAGS AS A RESULT, THE DURNITURE TORE A SMALL HOLE IN ONE BAG.  HAZ MAT WAS CALLED AND INFORMED US OF HANDLING PROCEDURES.  THEY TORN BAG AND CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

SPILL WAS REPORTED TO SUPERVISOR KEITH KELLAR.  THEN WE CHECKED THE TRAILER AND FREIGHT, AFTER WE CALLED HAZMAT AND THEY DEPARTMENT OF DEFENSE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HOTLINE.  WE STRIPPED TRAILER CLEAN OFF MESS AND DISPOSED OF BUCKET.

IN THE MEANTIME ANOTHER EMPLOYEE GOT SOME ON HIS HAND. MEETNGS HAVE BEEN HELD WITH EACH SHIFT OF EMPLOYEES ON PROPER PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW ON ANY HAZMAT SPILL. 1) REPORT AT ONCE TO THE SUPERVISOR. 2) CLEAR AWAY FROM THE AREA UNTIL IT HAS BEEN CHECKED COMPLETELY BY THE SUPERVISOR AND A DECISION HAS BEEN MADE. 3) IF ON A FORKLIFT TURN OFF ENGINE, PULL THE KEY OUT OF IT AND REPORT IT. 4) NEVER ATTEMPT TO CLEAN IT UP YOURSELF. 5) HANDLE WITH CAUTION ANY HAZ. MAT.

column168: ON MAY 22, 1995 AT 2:30 PM I RECEIVED A CALL FROM MY DRIVER STATING THAT A 150 LB. CYLINDER OF CHLORINE HAD FALLEN OFF THE LIFT GATE OF HIS TRUCK DURING A DELIVERY.  WHEN THE CYLINDER HIT THE GROUND, THE PROTECTIVE BONNET WAS KNOCKED OFF, THE VALVE WAS BENT AND CRACKED.  THIS RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 61 LBS. OF CHLORINE.  THE MIDWAY FIRE DEPT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND APPLIED AND "A KIT" WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE OF CHLORINE.  NO KNOW ACUTE OR CHRONIC PROBLEMS ARE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS RELEASE.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEAUSRE, PERSONNEL INVOLVED WERE ADVISED TO VISIT A PHYSICIAN FOR OBSERVATION.

DAMAGE NOTED UPON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION, NORRISTOWN.  BAGS WERE TORN, REPAIRED WITH TAPE.  CONSIGNEE REFUSED SHIPMENT, ARRANGING FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.  COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED WITH BETTER PACKAGING.

AN INCIDENT OCCURRED IN ENVIRITES FACILITY PARKING LOT RESULTING IN A SPILL OF HAZARDOUS WASTE.  APPROXIMATELY 18,000 TO 20,000 POUNDS OF SOLIDIFIED WASTE RESIDUE WAS RELEASED WHEN A DUMP TRAILER WAS HYDRAULICALLY LIFTED WITH THE INTENT OF REMOVING RAINWATER FROM THE CONTAINERS TARP.  THE WEIGHT OF THE LOAD AGAINST THE TRAILS REAR GATE CAUSED THE SAFETY LATCHES TO BREAK LOOSE, AND RELEASE THE WASTE (F006, F019 LISTED WASTE).  SPILLED RESIDUES WERE CONFINED WITHIN FACILITY BOUNDARIES, AND TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER BY FRONT-END LOADED.  THE SPILL AREA WAS PRESSURE WASHED.  CLEAN-UP EQUIPMENT WAS DECONTAMINED. APPROXIMELTY 10-15 GALLON OF RINSATE FROM CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WAS COLLECTED AND TREATED IN THE FACILITYS LIQUIDS PROCESSING UNIT.  SAFETY LATCHES WERE REPAIRED AND WELDED BACK IN PLACE.  DRIVERS AND PLANT OPERATORS HAVE BEEN INFORMED THAT REMOVAL OF RAINWATER FROM CONTAINER TARP'S WILL BE ACCOMPLISHED BY PUMPING OR OTHER MEANS THAT DO NOT NECESSITATE THE RAISING OF A LOADED TRAILER, AND THAT APPLICATION OF THE HYDRAULIC LIFT MECHANISM IS PROPER ONLY WHEN DUMPING A LOAD.

column168: DURING SORT OPERATIONS, AN ODOR RAISED SUSPICIONS ABOUT THE CONTENTS.  THE BOX WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR IN ANY WAY IDENTIFIED AS A DANGEROUS GOOD. INTERNAL INSPECTION DETERMINED THE SECONDARY INNER PACKAGES WERE MARKED "CONSUMER COMMODITY" AND THE MOST INNER CANS WERE AEROSAL PAINT.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED WHO SAID THIER PACKING SLIPS DENOTE "ASTERISKS" THAT ARE SUPPOSE TO INCIDATE TO THEIR WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEES THAT THE ITEM IS A DANGEROUS GOOD.  IT APPEARS THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT CATH THE ASTERISK IN THIS INSTANCE.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED OF THE "UNDECLARED" DANGEROUS GOOD SHIPMENT.

TRUCK WAS TRANSFERING CHEMICAL INTO CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK. CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK DID NOT HAVE AMPLE ROOM FOR DELIVERY. CONSIGNEE'S TANK'S VOLUME GAUGE WAS FAULTY. CHEMICAL OVERFLOWED INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA. CONSIGNEE HANDLED SPILLED CHEMICALS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0530 HOURS ON MAY 27TH, TWO CARS INSPECTORS SMELLED A CHEMICAL ODOR AROUND TRACK #4 IN NORTH YARD.  THE SMELL EMINATED FROM TANK CAR NATX78414.  BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR D.E. SULLIVAN AND THE SHIPPERS REPRESENTATIVES INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND IT TO BE LEAKING A VAPOR FROM THE JUNNCTURE OF THE MANWAY AND THE MANYWA COVER, TOWARD THE "A" END OF THE CAR.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET MISSING.  THE SHIPPER LEFT THE YARD TO SECURE A GASKET.  UPON HIS RETURN, HE AND SULLIVAN INSTALLED THE GASKET AND SCURED THE MANWAY COVER. THE CAR WAS MOVED SLIGHTLY TO AGITATE THE LOAD AND CONFIRM THAT THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION AT 1400 HOURS.

column168: DRIVER CALLED IN WITH DAMAGED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PKG IN REAR OF CAR.  I INSTRUCTED HIM NOT TO TOUCH PKG AND ASK HIM IF PACKAGE WAS GENERATING FUMES OR SMOKING.  HE SAID NO AND SAID HE COULD SEE 5-PART FORM AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS A CORROSIVE #8.  I TOLD HIM TO KEEP OUT OF THE PACKAGE CAR AND I WOULD COME TO THE DELIVERY POINT TO RESPOND TO DAMAGE PKG. AFTER LEAKING PKG AND WAS SECURE I OFF LOADED HIS CAR INTO ANOTHER CAR AND BROUGHT DAMAGED PKGS BACK TO THE BUILDING AND FOLLOWED PROPER DMP PROCEDURES.

ON SATURDAY, MAY 27, 1995, AT ABOUT 4:30 A.M., A FIRE WAS DISCOVERED ON A M & M DUMP TRAILER CONTAINING SOLID HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DURING TRANSPORTATION.  THIS OCCURRED WHILE THE TRUCK/TRAILER WAS STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 28 AND INTERSTATE 20 IN LIVINGSTON, AL.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE USING WATER.  THE FIRE FIGHTING WATER LEAKED FROM THE TRAILER AND RESULTED IN A RELEASE ESTIMATED AT ABOUT 500-1000 GALLONS WHICH RAN ONTO THE PARKINGS LOT OF THE TRUCK STOP.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE RELEASE ON THE PARKING LOT AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED ON THE LIQUID.  THE ABSORBENT AND SOIL WAS THEN CLEANED UP AND PLACED ON ROLL OFFS FOR STORAGE.  NONE OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL LEFT THE PARKING LOT OF THE TRUCK STOP.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ABOUT 20-25 TONS OF SOIL WAS CLEANED UP.  SAMPLES OF THE SOIL HAVE BEEN TESTED FOR HAZARDOUS CONSTITUENTS USING THE TCLP TEST WHICH INDICATED THAT THE SOIL WAS NON HAZARDOUS.  HOWEVER, OUT OF AN ABUNDANCE OF CAUTION, THE SOIL WILL BE DISPOSED OF AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE.

ON MAY 8, 1995, AT 0145, ADDIE CAMPTON, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, AND ALAN HENDERSON, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TECHNICIAN RESPONED TO AN ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE SCENE, WE DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  WE THEN BEGAN OUR INSPECTION OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  ONE THE INSIDE WAS A ONE GALLON METAL RECEPTACLE CONTAINING "FUEL AVIATION", "UN1863". ON INSPECTION OF THE RECEPTACLE, WE FOUND THE SCREW TYPE CLOSURE TO BE LOOSE. THERE WAS ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LOST, APPROXIMATLEY .005 LITRE, WHICH WAS ABSORBED B THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS A SPECIFICATION 4G BOX.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM DUE TO THE ODOR.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR FAILURE OF THIS BOX WAS INSUFFICIENT CUSHIONING MATERIAL, ALLOWING RUBBING AND ABRADING OF THE INNER CONTENTS CAUSING THE UNSECURED CLOSURES TO LOOSEN.  THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0239.

SCHNEIDER NATIONAL TRAILER NUMBER 418808 ARRIVED AT ADVANCE TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, 5325 CANAL ROAD, GARFIELD HTS., OHIO, APPROXIMATELY 7:00 P.M., ON MAY 3, 1995. THIS WAS A LOAD MISCELLANEOUS FREIGHT ORIGINATED BY SOUTHEASTERN FREIGHT LINES, INC. AT THEIR CHARLOTTE, N.C. FACILITY, FOR TRANSFER TO ADVANCE TRANSPORTATION COMPANY. THE SCHNEIDER NATIONAL DRIVER, JEFF BROWN, OPENED THE DOORS TO THE TRAILER AND ADVISED ADVANCE DOCK PERSONNEL AND ADVANCE SUPERVISOR, DAVE SULZER, THAT THERE WAS A VERY STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER, AND THAT THE TRAILER HAS POISONOUS SHIPMENTS ON BOARD. (SHIPPING PAPERS ATTACHED). MR. SULZER CHECKED THE LOAD MANIFEST AND SAW THAT THERE WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS ON THIS TRAILER, INCLUDING POISONOUS INHALATION SHIPMENT OF CYLINDERS. HE THEN WENT TO THE DOCK TO CHECK THE LOAD AND FOUND A VERY STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER, THAT WAS SPREADING ONTO THE DOCK AREA. HE SAW THE GAS CYLINDERS LAYING LOOSE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, BUT BY THEN HIS EYES AND THROAT WERE BURNING. MR. SULZER THEN CALLED BOB KANE, TERMINAL MANAGER, BUT HE WAS NOT HOME. HE LEFT A MESSAGE TO CALL IN. DAVE THEN TRIED TO CONTACT JERRY SCHENKER, REGIONAL SAFETY MANAGER AND GOT PATCHED THROUGH TO HIM AT HOME, AT ABOUT 8:00 TO 8:30 P.M. MR. SCHENKER TOLD DAVE TO CONTACT SCHNIEDER'S SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND ADVISE THEM TO THE SITUATION AND THAT THEY SHOULD TAKE THE NECESSARY ACTIONS. THIS LOAD OF FREIGHT, AT THIS POINT IN TIME, HAD NOT BEEN TOUCHED BY ADVANCE TRANSPORTATION, AND SAFETY TECHNICALLY, WAS STILL IN THE POSSESSION OF SCHNEIDER NATIONAL. DAVE MADE CONTACT WITH MR. TONY ANDERSON AT SCHNEIDER NATIONAL SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND GAVE HIM THE DETAILS OF THE SITUATION. MR. ANDERSON THEN CONTACTED THE OHIO E.P.A. SHORTLY THEREAFTER, THE GARFIELD HEIGHTS FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND BEGAN EVACUATION THE TERMINAL AND SURROUNDING AREA. (FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORT ATTACHED). BOB KANE, TERMINAL MANAGER, ARRIVED AT THE TERMINAL AT 9:45 P.M. FROM 9:45 P.M., MR. KANE COORDINATED WITH THE SITE COMMANDER, TONY CALLOVA, FIRE CHIEF, GARFIELD HEIGHTS AND MR. REGINALD BROWN, EMERGENCY RESPONSE SUPERVISOR, OHIO ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, TWINSBURG, OHIO. ALL TEST INDICATED THERE WAS NO PRESENCE OF ANY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, BUT THEY COULD NOT DETERMINE WHAT CAUSING THE STRONG ODOR. AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 A.M., CHIEF CALLOVA, AND MR. BROWN DETERMINED THAT MR. KANE HAS TO CALL IN A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL REMOVAL COMPANY TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER AND MAKE A DETERMINATION AS TO WHAT ACTION NEEDED TO BE TAKEN NEXT. MR. KANE, CALLED SAMSEL SERVICES COMPANY, CLEVELAND, OHIO, AND THEY ARRIVED AT THE TERMINAL WITH A FIVE MAN TEAM AT ABOUT 5:00 A.M. THIS TEAM UNLOADED THE TRAILER, AND INSPECTED ALL THREE HAZ MAT SHIPMENTS. THEIR FINDINGS ARE CONTAINED IN A SEPARATE REPORT, IN SUMMARY, NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE OCCURRED. THE CAUSE OF THE ODOR WAS A SHIPMENT OF EMPTY DRUMS THAT HAD CONTAINED A PESTICIDE LIQUID. THE VENTED BUNGS ON THE DRUMS WERE NOT PROPERLY SECURED, AL

ROB MARTENSON, WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 15-9645, SMELLED STRONG ODOR. HE PULLED ONE SKID OF THE SHIPMENT OUT AND FOUND 4 STEEL GALLON CONTAINERS CRUSHED. MOST OF THE CONTENTS SPILLED HAD EVAPORATED. APPEARED TO HAVE OCCURED ENROUTE DUE TO THE LACK OF DAMAGE USED IN LOAD.

MR JEFFRIES WAS UNLOADING TRAILER 17-9753 AND NOTICED CLEAR LIQUID UNDERNEATH SHIPMENT. AN EIGHT HUNDRED POUND, LONG SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF DAMAGED FREIGHT AND WAS CRUSHING IT. THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS RECOOPED AND LEAKAGE CLEANED.

column168: AT 1155 HRS ON 5/8/95, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY MTO RICK FOLKER.  HE ADVISED THAT CARMAN HAD REPORTED TANK CAR NATX 29911, CONTAINING MTBE'S, LOCATED ON EAST DEPARTURE TRACK 3 WAS LEAKING.  ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM MANWAY COVER AND BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED BETWEEN THE RAILS AND EVAPORTING UPON CONTACT WITH GROUND AND OUTSIDE ATMOSPHERE.  INSPECTION REVEALED CAR WAS SELL FULL, THUS CAUSING PRODCUT TO LEAK FROM CAR DUE TO EXPANSION AND IMPROPER SECUREMENT. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS FAULTY, STRETCHED OR OVERSIZED, THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN 3/4 TURN, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP LOOSE 1/2 TURN AND THE GASKET TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP WAS MISSING.  AFTER DETERMINING THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED, MGR LERCH OFF LOADED 550 GALLONS OF PRODUCT INTTO A PROTABLE FUEL TANK WHICH ALLOWED ENOUGH OUTAGE FOR PRODUCT EXPANSION TEMPORARILY.  MGR LERCH THEN CONTACTED SHIPPER, COASTAL CHEMICAL AND ADVISED MR. JIM WIDRIG, MR OF SAFETY AND STANDARDS AND MR. TYRON SEVHLA, TRAFFIC COORDINATOR.  A CHECK OF LOADING RECORDS INDICATED CAR WAS LOADED WITH 29,129 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  CAR'S RATED CAPACITY IS 29,211 GALLONS, WHICH ONLY ALLOWED 82 GALLONS OF OUTAGE FOR EXPANSION.  A 3% OUTAGE OF CAR'S CAPACIT EQUALS 876 GALLONS.  ON 5/10/95, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE BY COASTAL CHEMICAL AND CAR WAS REDUCTED ANOTHER 600 GALLONS.  MGR LERCH THEN PROPERLY SECURED ALL FITTINGS, REPLACED GASKETS AND RELEASED CAR FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: ON MAY 24, 1995 AT 6:45 AM A TRACOTR TRAILER COMBINATION, 2253-8170, OPERATED BY AN AIR LIQUIDE AMERICA EMPLOYEE, WAS TRANSPORTING 42,500 POUNDS OF LIQUID CARBON DIOXIDE FROM DELAWARE CITY, DELAWARE TO KUTZTOWN, PENNSYLVANIA.  WHILE EXITING THE OFF RAMP FROM 476N TO 76W THE TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE.  AIR LIQUIDE PERSONNEL WERE FIRST CONTACTED AT 8:00AM EST IN HOUST, TEXAS.  THE FIRST AIR LIQUIDE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 9:30, THE SECOND AT 9:45 AND THE THIRD TAM AT 10:00AM/  PRODUCT TRANSFER FROM THE DAMAGED UNIT WAS COMPLETED BY 11:00AM SIMULTANEOUS WITH THE ARRIVAL OF THE CRANE AND WRECKERS.  AT NO TIME WAS PRODUCT RELEASED OR LEAKED DUE TO THE ACCIDENT.  CARBON DIOXIDE IS A NON-FLAMMABLE, LIQUEFIED GAS TRANSPORTED VIA MC331 CARGO TANK.  THE MC331 CARGO TANK IS PRESSURIZED AT ALL TIMES WITH PRODUCT ON BOARD.  THE MC331 CARGO TANK WIS ALSO EQUIPPED WITH SAFETY RELIEF DEVICES DESIGNED TO RELEIVE PRESSURE IN THE CARGO TANK AUTOMATICALLY.  AIR LIQUIDE'S CARBON DIOXIDE CARGO TANKS ARE EQUIPPED WITH THREE AUTOMATIC PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICES AS WELL AS MANUAL CONTROLS.  EVACUATION AND ROAD CLOSURES WER EORDERED BY THE COMMONWEALTH OF PENNSYLVANIA, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES.   AIT LIQUIDE DID NOT ENDORSE THAT DECISION AND RECOMMENDED AGAINST IT DUE TO THE FACT THAT CARBON DIOXIDE IS NON-FLAMMABLE AND WILL NO SUPPORT COMBUSTION.  IN THE EVENT OF A RUPTURE OR SUDDEN DEPRESSURIZATION, CO2 WILL BECOME DRY ICE. (SOILD CO2).

column168: UNION PACIFIC REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, PORTLAND, WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS DAVID DODGE, HINKLE YARD, TANK CAR GATX 49693, RESIDUE, L/C ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, LIQUIFIED WAS LEAKING. TRAVELED TO HINKLE YARD AND INSPECTION DEVELOPED MIDLAND A1225BN SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS LEAKING APPARENTLY ACCOUNT DEFECTIVE "O" RINGS. TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED PENDING REPAIRS. column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT ZERWECK WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER RICHARD LOYA AT EL PASO OF ACFX 94215 LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY WHILE SWITCHING. ZERWECK TRAVELED TO EL PASO AND INSPECTED THE LOAD OF STYRENE MONOMER. SEAL REXENE 270937 WAS REMOVED FROM THE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND WHEN OPENED NO GASKET WAS FOUND. THE SURFACES WERE CLEAN. A GORE-TEX 1/2" GASKET WAS APPLIED AND THE MANWAY COVER PLATE SECURED. SEAL REXENE 270938 WAS REMOVED FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND THE VALVES INSPECTED, NO PROBLEMS FOUND. MARGIE HAYS WITH REXENE AT ODESSA WAS CONTACTED AT 915-333-8231 AND ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM. A NEW GASKET WILL BE INSTALLED AT DESTINATION. THE PRODUCT WAS SLOSHED AT THE MANWAY HAD EVAPORATED WITH NO GROUND CONTACT.

column168: UNION PACIFIC REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, PORTLAND,OR., WAS NOTIFIED BY UNION PACIFIC MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE RANDY BULLOCK, HINKLE, OR., THAT STEPHEN SMITH, FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION, DANIEL VICKERS, IDAHO PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION, AND GORDON KOROPCHUK, TRANSPORTS CANADA, HAD BAD ORDERED TANK CAR PROX 41125 AT EASTPORT, ID., ACCOUNT LEAKING CONDITION. IN COMPANY WITH MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY SAND COVI, POCATELLO, ID., TRAVELED TO EASTPORT. INSPECTION DEVELOPED LEAK CONSISTED OF VAPORS FROM SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. VAPOR PRESSURE OF TANK CAR WAS BLED OFF AND SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS DISASSEMBLED. RUBBER "O" RINGS SHOWED EVIDENCE OF ABRADING. THE "O" RINGS WERE TURNED OVER AND RE-ADJUSTED AND SAFETY VALVE WAS RE-ASSEMBLED. THIS TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED ON MAY 17, 1995, NO EVIDENCE OF ANY VAPOR RELEASE WAS FOUND. NEW "O" RINGS WERE NOT AVAILABLE FOR INSTALLATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 0900 HRS ON THE 31ST OF MAY 1995. MGR CTS RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED TANK CAR TCDX13197 WAS FOUND LEAKING AT GREEN RIVER, WY. THE CAR WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP. CAR SHOWS LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID. INSPECTION REVEALED AN OBVIOUS PROBLEM, AS THE FILL HOLE COVER PLATE AND PART OF THE LOCKING BAR ARE MISSING FROM THE CAR. A RODABOUGH AND THE CAR DEPARTMENT CUT A PLATE FROM 5/8 STOCK AND MGR RODABOUGH HAD THE CAR DEPARTMENT CUT A PLATE FROM 5/8 STOCK AND MGR RODBOUGH APPLIED GORTEX GASKET, THE CAR WAS THE SECURED USING THE PLATE, LOCKING INTO POSITION WITH C-CLAMPS, THE CAR AND THE ADJACENT CARS ON BOTH ENDS WERE WASHED WITH WATER AND SODIUM BICARBONATE SOLUTION. SPECIAL ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED THE 14 MILES TO ITS ROCK SPRINGS DESTINATION. MR. ED PAGER OF MAGMA COPPER OF SAN MEGUEL ARIZONA WAS INFORMED REGARDING THE PROBLEMS WITH THE CAR. HE WAS CONCERNED AND INDICATED THEY WOULD TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

UPRR CAR FOREMAN KENNY AMOS REPORTED THAT TANK CAR ACFX 80139 WAS LEAKING. THE CAR WAS IN 22 BOWL AND WOULD BE ISOLATED TO TRACK 558. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND NOTED THAT THE THERMOMETER WELL WAS LEAKNG VAPOR. WHEN THE CAP WAS REMOVED THERE WAS A GENTLE BLOWING OF VAPOR. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE "O" RING ON THE CAP WAS NOT INTACT. THIS WAS REPLACED AND THE CAP SECURED, STOPPING THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS HELD IN BO STATUS PENDING TRANSFER OF LADING. FARMLAND REPRESENTATIVE JACK CURRY, 816-459-6587 WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT  AND DESIGNATED ACFX 17211 AS THE TANK CAR EMPTY FOR TRANSFER. CHEMTREC JOE MILAZZO WAS NOTIFIED AT 1255, DATE., REPORT #35966. THE TRANSFER WAS DONE ON JUNE 1, 1995. UPRR PERSONNEL BOB STINE, TOM ROBINSON, ARLA ROQUET, GEOFF REEDER, AND MIKE KELLY WERE ON SCENE AT 0600 HRS TO AFFECT TRANSFER. THE TRANSFER WENT WITHOUT INCIDENT AND WAS COMPLETED AT 1600 HRS. ACFX 80139 WAS STENCILED "LEAKY TANK" AND RELEASED. TANK CAR ACFX 17211, NOW LOADED, WAS SENT ON TO CONSIGNEE.

column168: ON JUNE 22, 1995, ISLAND AIR FLIGHT 1009 WAS BOUND FOR PRINCEVILLE. THE FLIGHT CREW COULD SMELL WHAT THEY DESCRIBED AS NAIL POLISH REMOVER OR LIGHTER FLUID. THE ODOR DISAPPEARED WHEN THEY LEVELED OFF. UPON ARRIVAL IN PRINCEVILLE THEY LOCATED A BOX THAT WAS SLIGHTLY DAMP IN ONE CORNER. INSIDE THEY FOUND ONE (1) RED PLASTIC BOTTLE (ABOUT 1 PINT) AND ONE (1) CLEAR PLASTIC BOTTLE (ABOUT 2 PINTS) WHICH BOTH CONTAINED WHITE GASOLINE. THEY ALSO FOUND A SINGLE BURNER CAMPING STOVE. THE BOX AND CONTENTS WERE IMMEDIATELY CONFISCATED FROM THE PASSENGER AND THE MANAGER-AIRPORTS SERVICES WAS CONTACTED IN HONOLULU FOR FURTHER ACTION. THE BOX IS BEING HELD AT PRINCEVILLE STATION UNTIL THE FAA NOTIFIES ISLAND AIR THAT IT CAN BE RELEASED.
I WAS CALLED TO PACKAGE CAR; DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE; USED DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET AND CLEANED UP.
NO REMARKS

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: AT 0850 HRS CENTRAL TIME, TUESDAY MAY 23RD MGR. C.T.S. HARRY W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. LEO TIERNY, DIRECTOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGEMENT, WHO RECEIVED HIS INFORMATION FROM MR. PETE LOCK M.T.O. AT SALT LAKE THAT TRAILER CONTAINER TRIU228372 TO BE LEAKING SOME TYPE OF ACID. THE SHIPPER, DEFENSEDEPOT ODGEN AND ERICKSON INC, WERE CALLED ARRIVING AT THE SAME TIME 0900 HRS, MOUNTAIN TIME. THE OGDEN RESPONSE TEAM OPENED THE CONTAINER AND EXTRACTED 1 DRUM THAT WAS AFTER THE INITIAL DRUM WAS REMOVED AND VISIBLE FUMES DECREASED THE RAIL CAR WITH THE REMAINING DRUMS WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE NORTH END OF THE YARD, WHERE THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED AND PLACED INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA THAT HAD BEEN REPAIRED BY ERICKSON INC. ERICKSON COMMENCED TO EXTRACT DRUMS FOR INTEGRITY INSPECTION. ONE ADDITIONAL DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. IT WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM AND DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURES BEGAN. THE PROJECT WAS COMPLETE AT 2000 HRS. WITH ALL DRUMS BEING RELOADED INTO THE CONTAINER AND BLOCKING AND BRACING COMPLETE. ON MAY 24TH THE CONTAMINATED SOIL SURROUNDING THE RAIL CAR ORIGINAL LOCATION IN GOAT PIT ONE WAS EXCAVATED, THE SOIL AND ROCKS PLACED INTO POLY DRUMS. WHEN POSSIBLE, ALL FREE LIQUIDS WERE CAPTURED AND PLACED INTO POLY DRUMS STABILIZATION. WHEN THESE OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETE THE POLY DRUMS WERE PLACED ON PALLETS. THERE WERE A TOTAL OF SIX DRUMS OF CONTAMINATED MATERIAL AND ONE MORE OVERPACK. ALL WERE SHIPPED BACK TO DEFENSE DEPOT OGDEN FOR MANAGEMENT. INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE SHIPPER HAD PLACED PALLETS SIDE BY SIDE EACH WITH THREE DRUMS BANDED ON THEM, THIS SYSTEM LEFT A VOID, THE SHIPPER PLACED AN UNBANDED DRUM IN THE VOID AND FAILED TO BLOCK OR BRACE THE LOAD, DURING SHIPPING THE DRUMS SHIFTED. IT IS EVIDENT THAT THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE THE RESULT OF DRUM MOVEMENT ON THE CORNERS OF THE PALLETS.

column168: (A)(B)(C)(D)(E)(F)TRAIN X97 TRAVELING EASTBOUND AT APPROXIMATELY 52 MPH DERAILED THE 21ST THROUGH 44TH HEAD CARS.  INCLUDED IN THE DERAILMENT WERE 17 LOADED TANK CARS OF PETROLEUM ASPHALT BEING TRANSPORTED AS AN ELEVATED TEMPERATURE MATERIAL. THE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM 6 TANK CARS LISTED ON ATTACHMENT 1. ALL CARS LISTED WERE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLETS, CARS GATX 43095 AND UTLX 645274 SUSTAINED HEAVY TANK SHELL DAMAGE WHICH RESULTED IN PRODUCT LOSS. IT CAN BE NOTED FROM THE ATTACHED PHOTOGRAPHS THAT THE CARS WERE "STACKED IN" AGAINST EACH OTHER MAKING INITIAL DAMAGE ASSESSMENT DIFFICULT. SEVERAL TANK CARS WERE IN A POOL OF ASPHALT AND IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO TELL WHICH CAR OR CARS THE PRODUCT CAME FROM UNTIL THE CARS WERE MOVED AND OPENED FOR TRANSFER. ALL THE DAMAGED CARS WERE TRANSFERED TO TRUCKS FOR FURTHER HANDLING OF THE PRODUCT. PRODUCT LOSS FIGURES WERE OBTAINED AFTER THE CONTENTS OF THE CARS WERE TRANFERED AND SUBTRACTING THAT AMOUNT FROM THE AMOUNT ORIGINALLY SHIPPED, ALLOWING FOR RESIDUE REMAINING IN EACH CAR AFTER TRANSFER. DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT, THE RUN-OFF AND ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE WERE MINIMAL. NO PRODUCT REACHED SURFACE WATER. THE DAMAGE CAUSED BY THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS LIMITED TO ROADBED MATERIALS AND WAS ALSO MINIMAL. THERE WERE NO PERSONAL INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. ATTACHMENTS: LIST OF CARS INVOLVED, DIAGRAMS, PHOTOGRAPHS. SEE REPORT 95071186A SEE REPORT
